{{Quote|But it came to pass that a Daemon (as popular opinion supposed) in his [[phrontisterium|secret workshops]] devised certain abominable machines, to which he gave the name Motores.|Excerpt from the story<ref name=telegraph>{{webcite|author=[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/authors/d/da-de/dalya-alberge/ Dalya Alberge]|articleurl=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2025/05/30/morris-motors-boss-may-inspired-tolkien-villain/|articlename=Morris Motors boss may have inspired Tolkien villain|dated=30 May 2025|website=Telegraph|accessed=30 May 2025}}</ref>}}

The '''Daemon''' was popularly<ref name=telegraph/> believed<ref name=telegraph/> to be a [[demon]] who manufactured machines called Motores "in his [[phrontisterium|secret workshops]]"<ref name=telegraph/> at [[Vaccipratum]] to block "the streets, asphyxiate the inhabitants, and finally explode".<ref name=Bio>{{B|IV}}, Chapter VI: The Storyteller, p. 163 (footnote)</ref> The people of [[Bovadium]] later worshipped his<ref name=telegraph/> Motores "and the traffic jams blocking the roads in and around" Bovadium.<ref name=satire>[[Clyde S. Kilby]], ''[[Tolkien and The Silmarillion|Tolkien & The Silmarillion]]'', II. "Summer with Tolkien", "Some Notes on “Smith of Wootton Major”", p. 36</ref> As a consequence, the city was destroyed.<ref name=Bio/>

== Etymology ==
''Vaccipratum'' is a Latin name meaning "cow pasture",<ref name=telegraph/> "Cowley",<ref name=telegraph/> or "cow-meadow".<ref>{{webcite|author=[[John Garth]]|articleurl=https://steady.page/en/john-garth-on-tolkiens-life-and-works/posts/80a64201-1df3-42d8-a6ec-cf40e9efd5b4|articlename=Tolkien’s road goes on – but there’s traffic ahead at Bovadium|dated=24 May 2025|website=[https://steady.page/en/john-garth-on-tolkiens-life-and-works/posts John Garth on Tolkien's life and works]|accessed=30 June 2025}}</ref>

== Inspiration ==
In [[Humphrey Carpenter]]'s [[1977]] [[J.R.R. Tolkien: A Biography|biography]] of [[J.R.R. Tolkien]], it is mentioned in a summary of ''[[The End of Bovadium|The Bovadium Fragments]]'' that the "Daemon of Vaccipratum" is "a reference to [[Wikipedia:Lord Nuffield|Lord Nuffield]] and his motor-works at Cowley".<ref name=Bio/>

